Step 5 - Read mystery.pdf for clues

    import fitz
    doc = fitz.open('mystery.pdf')
    print(doc[0].get_text())
    # "Welcome to the deeper layers.
    #  A wise phantom once carried a code.
    #  A haunting spectre guards the final door."

Two steghide passwords are hidden in plain English here:
    phantom -> carrier.jpg
    spectre -> final.jpg

Remember: CTF PDF files often contain clues in their visible text, not just metadata.
Always extract and read the text before moving on.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 6 - Steghide on carrier.jpg -> QR code

    steghide extract -sf carrier.jpg -p phantom -f
    # wrote extracted data to "qr.png"

Decode the QR code:

    from pyzbar.pyzbar import decode
    from PIL import Image
    print(decode(Image.open('qr.png'))[0].data)
    # b'ZmhjcmVfZnJwZXJnX25yZg=='

Decode base64:

    import base64
    print(base64.b64decode('ZmhjcmVfZnJwZXJnX25yZg==').decode())
    # 'fhcre_frperg_nrf'

Apply ROT13:

    import codecs
    print(codecs.encode('fhcre_frperg_nrf', 'rot13'))
    # 'super_secret_aes'

This is the AES decryption key.

Remember: When you see random-looking lowercase strings with underscores, always try
ROT13. It's one of the most common simple obfuscation layers in CTFs.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 7 - Steghide on final.jpg -> encrypted payload

    steghide extract -sf final.jpg -p spectre -f
    # wrote extracted data to "flag.enc"

    file flag.enc
    # openssl enc'd data with salted password

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Step 8 - Decrypt flag.enc with AES key

    openssl enc -d -aes-256-cbc -in flag.enc -pass pass:super_secret_aes -pbkdf2
    # KH3L0{44kh1R_44nDAr_GH0S_H1_G44Y_B3T4}

